</table>
<p>The <b>reflected binary code</b>, also known as <b>Gray code</b> after <a href="/wiki/Frank_Gray_(researcher)" title="Frank Gray (researcher)">Frank Gray</a>, is a <a href="/wiki/Binary_numeral_system" title="Binary numeral system">binary numeral system</a> where two successive values differ in only one bit.</p>
<p>The reflected binary code was originally designed to prevent spurious output from <a href="/wiki/Electromechanical" title="Electromechanical" class="mw-redirect">electromechanical</a> <a href="/wiki/Switch" title="Switch">switches</a>. Today, Gray codes are widely used to facilitate <a href="/wiki/Error_correction" title="Error correction" class="mw-redirect">error correction</a> in digital communications such as <a href="/wiki/Digital_terrestrial_television" title="Digital terrestrial television">digital terrestrial television</a> and some <a href="/wiki/DOCSIS" title="DOCSIS">cable TV</a> systems.</p>
